knowledge_graph.title: Corn chip
knowledge_graph.description: Corn chips are a snack food made from cornmeal fried in oil or baked, usually in the shape of a small noodle or scoop. Corn chips are thick, rigid, very crunchy, have the strong aroma and flavor of roasted corn, and are often heavily seasoned with salt.

related_questions.question: What's the difference between a tortilla chip and a corn chip?
related_questions.snippet: While corn chips and tortilla chips are both made from corn, the corn in tortilla chips is subjected to the nixtamalization process, resulting in a milder flavor and aroma, and a less rigid texture. Tortilla chips also tend to be larger, thinner, less fatty, and less salty than corn chips.

related_questions.question: What are Mexican corn chips called?
related_questions.snippet: In Mexico, we called tortilla chips, totopos. They are best known as originating from Zapotec peoples of the Mexican state of Oaxaca.
related_questions.title: Totopos or Tortilla Chips? - AlbaLisa

related_questions.question: Are corn chips healthy or unhealthy?
related_questions.snippet: Because corn chips are usually fried in oil, most of this fat is unsaturated fat -- a healthier alternative to saturated fat, which can clog your arteries. One serving of corn chips contains only 1.4 g of saturated fat. Like all plant foods, corn chips contain no cholesterol.

related_questions.question: What was the original corn chip?
related_questions.snippet: At a gas station, Doolin found a Mexican man making an extruded corn chip out of masa, frying it and selling little bags of the fried corn chips. They were fritos, "little fried things" — the beach food of Mexico.
